Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Composer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/composer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/composer-6-7)

The editability of a document in the Composer is controlled by the 'editable-document' element property. This property is configured during template creation. Each document element (block, list, image, text, table, etc.) can have its editability individually configured. The 'editable-document' property is interpreted during document serving and transformed to the 'editable-resolved' property, which can only be 'true' or 'false', indicating if the element is editable or not in the Composer. This can be checked in the debug window to investigate possible editability configuration problems:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Turning ON Debug settings*

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Show original IDX preview option*

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Debug window showing some editable elements*

The default editability in the Composer is 'false', meaning that if nothing is configured in the template, there will be almost no interactivity in the Composer (there are exceptions).

Editability is inheritable. If a parent element is editable, all its children will also be editable. Children elements can override this by setting their own editability.

If an element is not editable, the user cannot modify the elements properties or manipulate its children. This results in the behavior that in a non-editable section, the user cannot input text, format text, change image dimensions, split table cells, use form fields, etc.

If an element contains some non-editable children, it cannot be removed from the document even if it is in an editable area (except insertion points - see below).

## Insertion points editability
Currently, insertion points (IPs) are an exception to the above rules. To prevent accidental removal of an IP, the IP elements editability is hardcoded to be 'false'. Additionally, the direct child of an IP, which holds all the building blocks (BB), has its editability hardcoded to be 'true', allowing drag &amp; drop of BB into IP to work. The last exception is the contents node of BB, which is hardcoded to be 'false', to encourage BB edit through BB parameters, instead of direct editing in the document. If BB editability is needed directly in the document, the BB template needs to be configured to contain an editable container, ensuring editability of the entire BB content. Standard BB operations such as ADD, REMOVE, MOVE, MODIFY (with parameters), and REFRESH do not check the editability of the BB elements and are always available.

## Form fields editability
Form fields are also an exception to the above rules. Editability of form fields is controlled by the 'formfield-target' property configured during template creation. If the value is configured as 'intermediate', form fields will be editable in the Composer, but they wont be usable in the

final PDF. If the value is configured as 'final', form fields will only be editable in the final PDF. If the value is configured as 'both', the form field will be editable in both the Composer and the final PDF.

## Editability visualization
To help the user understand what is editable and what is not editable, the Composer supports two editability visualization options, which can be toggled in the bottom left corner:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*View menu*

If no value is checked, then editable and non-editable regions do not have any visual indication. Exceptions are form fields, which are always visualized in gray if they are not editable (in all modes).

If 'Show editable regions' is checked:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*View menu - show editable regions*

Editable regions are shown with a blue background, which is mixed with the existing background. Form fields and images have a blue overlay:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Sample editable region visualization*

If 'Show non-editable regions' is checked:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*View menu - show not editable regions*

Non-editable regions are shown with a gray background, which is also mixed with the existing background. Form fields and images have a gray overlay in this mode:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Sample not editable region visualization*
